# Development workflow (agentic-swe)

Follow this for **any code or config change** in this repository. It matches the protected-branch setup on GitHub (`main`, `uat`) and naming rules for short-lived branches.

## Branches

| Kind | Pattern | Purpose |
|------|---------|---------|
| Release | `main` | Production-ready history; **never commit directly** — merge via PR only. |
| Pre-release / integration | `uat` | Staging / acceptance; **never commit directly** — merge via PR only (typically `main` → `uat` or `feature/*` → `uat` when validating before `main`). |
| Feature | `feature/<short-kebab-topic>` | New capability or larger change. |
| Bugfix | `bugfix/<short-kebab-topic>` or `bug-fix/<short-kebab-topic>` | Defect fixes. |
| Hotfix | `hotfix/<short-kebab-topic>` | Urgent production-oriented fixes (same discipline as feature). |
| Maintenance | `chore/<short-kebab-topic>` | Tooling, CI, docs-only batches that are not product features. |

Do **not** use generic names like `dev`, `temp`, or owner-prefixed ad-hoc branches unless you are using an allowed prefix above. If GitHub rejects a push, rename the branch to match the convention.

## Session start

1. `git fetch origin` and base your work on **`origin/main`** unless the task explicitly targets **`uat`**.
2. Create a **new branch** before editing:

   `git checkout -b feature/my-change` (or `bugfix/…`, `chore/…`, etc.).

## Before every push

From the **repository root** (so `.npmrc` applies):

1. **`npm test`** — required.
2. If you changed anything under **`site/`** or site tooling, also run:
   - `npm run lint --prefix site`
   - `npm run build --prefix site`

Fix failures **before** pushing. Do not push to rely on CI to discover broken tests.

## Push and pull request

1. Commit on your feature branch with a clear message (see repo `git-identity-personal` rule for author email).
2. `git push -u origin <your-branch>`
3. Open a PR with **`gh`** (or the GitHub UI):
   - **Default base:** `main`
   - **Use base `uat`** only when the task is explicitly UAT/staging integration or the user asked to land changes on `uat` first.

   Example:

   `gh pr create --base main --head <your-branch> --title "…" --body "…"`

4. Do **not** merge from the agent unless the user asked you to handle merge/CI gates; the human (or policy) approves after review.

## Quick checklist

- [ ] On a **named** branch (`feature/*`, `bugfix/*`, `bug-fix/*`, `hotfix/*`, or `chore/*`).
- [ ] **Not** committing directly to `main` or `uat`.
- [ ] **`npm test`** passed locally (and site lint/build if applicable).
- [ ] Pushed to `origin` and **PR opened** (or user told you they will open it).

## GitHub rulesets (this repo)

Long-lived branches are protected on GitHub (no direct pushes; PR + CI + code owners, with admin bypass on pull requests as configured in the UI):

| Branch | Role |
|--------|------|
| `main` | Release / default — [ruleset in repo settings](https://github.com/surajSFDC/agentic-swe/rules) |
| `uat` | Pre-release / acceptance — same policy pattern as `main`; merge via PR after CI green |

**Promote `main` → `uat`:** open a PR with base `uat` and compare `main` (or merge `main` into a branch and PR). Do **not** use `git push origin main:uat` — rulesets block direct updates to `uat`.

Short-lived work uses the prefixes in the table above. **Branch-name enforcement** beyond that is handled here in Cursor; if you want server-side name patterns as well, add a **metadata / branch name** rule in **Settings → Rules → Rulesets** (the REST API may reject some pattern payloads on free-tier repos).

